# Single-line `continue` style (project preference)

When a loop guard's body is **only** a `continue;`, **do not** wrap that body in `{ }`. When it reads cleanly, place the `continue;` on the **same line** as the `if`.

## Preferred

Same line (preferred when the condition fits comfortably and is the simple "skip this iteration" guard):

```csharp
foreach (string key in keys)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(key)) continue;

    Process(key);
}
```

Two-line form is also fine when the condition is long or has side-effect-free pattern matching that benefits from a line of its own:

```csharp
foreach (KeyValuePair<string, ConfigSection> entry in sections)
{
    if (entry.Value is not { Enabled: true } enabled)
        continue;

    Apply(enabled);
}
```

## Avoid

Do not wrap a sole `continue;` in `{ }`:

```csharp
// Avoid
foreach (string key in keys)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(key))
    {
        continue;
    }

    Process(key);
}
```

## Scope

- Applies only when `continue;` is the **sole** statement in the `if` / `else if` body.
- Keep the **blank line before** the `if` per the project blank-line rule, **except** when the same-line form is the very first statement in the loop body.
- Multi-statement guards, `try` / `catch`, or anything that needs a local variable still use `{ }`.
- Same convention as **`SingleLineThrowNoBraces.mdc`** and the broader **`CSharp-EmbeddedStatements-NoBraces.mdc`**; this rule is the loop-guard companion.

## Rationale

A skip-iteration guard is the loop equivalent of a guard-clause `throw` or `return`. Removing the brace pair (and ideally the line) keeps the eye on the **happy path** below the guards.
